    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3904593910" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3904593910" />
    <a title="Jess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7336640-jess"><img alt="Jess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346493251p2/7336640.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3904593910?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jess" href="/user/show/7336640-jess">Jess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 0583319335" href="/book/show/18161504-problem-at-pollensa-bay-and-other-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7336640-jess?shelf=crime">crime</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3904593910" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4538054916676373787">This is a very odd round-up of stories. Some feature Christie fans&apos; favourite recurring detectives: there are two Poirot stories, two with Parker Pyne, and two centred around Mr Satterthwaite and Harley Quin. And then there are the last two stories, which are simply dramas - they are ok, but nothing special! When you&apos;re reading a Christie, you&apos;re always waiting for an odd or mysterious twist, and it comes as a disappointment when none arise.<br/><br/>Yellow Iris, one of the Poirot stories, is an interesti</span>
  <span id="freeText4538054916676373787" style="display:none">This is a very odd round-up of stories. Some feature Christie fans' favourite recurring detectives: there are two Poirot stories, two with Parker Pyne, and two centred around Mr Satterthwaite and Harley Quin. And then there are the last two stories, which are simply dramas - they are ok, but nothing special! When you're reading a Christie, you're always waiting for an odd or mysterious twist, and it comes as a disappointment when none arise.<br /><br />Yellow Iris, one of the Poirot stories, is an interesting read, as afficionados will enjoy seeing how Christie transformed it into the Poirot-less novel Sparkling Cyanide. Similarly, The Second Gong was reworked into the novella Dead Man's Mirror. Christie changes the killer and the motive in the expanded versions, so there are no spoilers!<br /><br />I enjoyed both Parker Pyne stories - they were light and diverting - and the second of the Harley Quin stories (The Love Detectives) is also an interesting little mystery. However, the first Harley Quin story in the book was actually written much later by Christie, in 1971, and it bears the same sad loss of style and brevity that marks Postern of Fate, the final novel she wrote. I'm sure it bears some interest for Christie scholars and completist, but I don't see how its place in this collection was justified, and I'm surprised Christie's estate allowed it to be released to the general public. It's a shame it's in this book, as it rather mars the collection as a whole and just made me feel sad at the loss of Christie's great talents for story-telling towards the end of her life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4538054916676373787" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


